{{Infobox stadium |stadium_name = Arto Tolsa Areena |fullname = Arto Tolsa Areena |nickname = |image = Arto Tolsa -areena 1.jpg |image_size = 250px |location = [[Kotka]], [[Finland]] |coordinates = {{Coord|60|27|27|N|26|56|23|E|region:FI-ES_type:landmark}} |built = |opened = 1952 |renovated = 2006 |closed = |demolished = |owner = [[Kotka|City of Kotka]] |operator = [[Kotka|City of Kotka]] |surface = [[Artificial turf|Artificial grass]] |construction_cost = |architect = |former_names = ''Kotkan urheilukeskus'' |tenants = [[Kotkan Työväen Palloilijat|KTP]] |seating_capacity = 4,780 (allseater) |dimensions = 105 x 65 m | }}
'''Arto Tolsa Areena''' is a [[football (soccer)|football]] [[stadium]] in [[Kotka]], [[Finland]]. It is the home stadium of [[Kotkan Työväen Palloilijat]] (KTP). The stadium holds 4,780 and was inaugurated in 1952 for the [[Helsinki Olympics]]. The stadium's record attendance was made during the Olympic Games in the [[Association football|football]] match between the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] and [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], the score having been 2–1 [[extra time|a.e.t.]].<ref>[http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1952/OR1952.pdf 1952 Summer Olympics official report.] p. 62.</ref> Depending on the source, the record is 10,000,<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197058/matches/match=32377/report.html FIFA Match Report ''Soviet Union – Bulgaria'' 16 July 1952.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022083858/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D512/edition%3D197058/matches/match%3D32377/report.html |date=22 October 2009 }}</ref> or 10,637 or 10,950.<ref>Harri Levänen: "Kyllä Urheilukeskukseen mahtui", ''Kymen Sanomat'', July 5, 2010.</ref>
Arto Tolsa Areena used to be known as "Urheilukeskus" ("Sports Center" in Finnish). It got its current name after it was renovated around the turn of millennium. The current name comes from [[Arto Tolsa]], who was a legendary [[Finland|Finnish]] player of Kotkan Työväen Palloilijat, the predecessor of KTP.
The covered main stand holds 2,500 spectators. The size of the pitch is 105 by 65 metres. The power of the lighting system is 1200 [[lux]].
At the beginning of the 2015 season, the pitch was converted to an artificial playing surface.
